<br>
Who said utility roles and tools weren't useful in groups?  Previous to trods though did you rely on that utility to maintain DPS?  I'm extremely happy for trods, because without them our DPS and damage in groups would be much lower.  Any magician worth their snuff was already summoning rods in groups well before trods existed, but trods were not a necessary component to maintain our damage margin, which indicates that our offensive nature is slipping, wouldn't you think?<br>
<br>
Your next argument will be we don't have to use trods to maintain DPS because we can canni pets.  Not having the epic, you may not understand the want to keep a 500 mana 5 minute recast pet, but having used it for nearly or more than a year I can tell you I dread resummoning it :)  As you know though I put alot of love into my pets -- muzzle, armor, weapons.. my pet is important to me and in places where I like to group my pet is a lifeline for my group as it proves crowd control and often is the tank, I can't canni pets -- and if canni pets is the solution to a mana chrisis to produce constant dps then where's my other missing utility spells, since it sounds like we're just poor wizzies then. :)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> True, support is much more required on raids, but then support beyond the minimum yields diminishing returns. When there are multiple mages on a raid, the support duties are easily shared, and mages can do what they do best: deal damage. While it is stressful to be the only mage on a raid, it is much more relaxing to have three or more mages. Likewise, it would hell to be the only shaman or enchanter on a raid.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If you were to break classes into three catagories and assign them a major or minor how would you classify mages?  Traditionally, and even still, in groups magicians have been damage (major), pets (major), utility (minor) -- while with the last two expansions and explicity with trods in Luclin utility has become more important, it is still a minor role in most groups, mages don't join a 6-man team to drop rods like they do on raids.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, classes like Shamans have traditionally been healers (minor), buffers (major), debuffers (major) and a minor in damage -- typically.  Their role in groups and raids doesn't change.  It may be that the role is split between the shamans on a raid, but that role is the same from level 1 to level 60.<br>
<br>
Magicians on a raid change their major/minors quite a bit.  We will typically minor in damage, pets and major in utility.  That in my books a complete change of role wouldn't you say?  Imagine walking into the first elemental filled zone in PoP and the group saying &quot;ok, Raz is the chanter,&quot; how out of place will that be?<br>
<br>
Aamilae Banadar<br>
